monitors.description:
1- Monitor the length of the queue for PAS full sync
2- Scheduler is putting tenants that has to be synced in the PAS full sync. It's tight to tenant scheduling in Scheduler service. In Ingestion service TenantPasSyncJobManager is processing messages and may reschedule the same tenant couple of times if number of role assignments are too big (it's 1000 RAs per 1 message)
3- This is being triggered when there are too much or too less messages in the queue.
4- If the queue length changes is a lot it can be either that nothing is being synced, or too much is being synced

Full Sync in the region cannot keep up with the ingress.
If left unchecked, queues will get backed up and eventually the backed up time will exceed storage queue SAS read expiry resulting in 403s

1- Monitor the length of the queue for normalizer
2- Normalizer is making list calls for each subscription to get the list of resources that needs to be synced.
3- This is being triggered when subscriptions scheduled are being dequeued.
4- If the queue length changes is a lot it can be either that nothing is being synced, or too much is being synced
5-6- Look to Scheduler TSG for future instructions (TODO oltkache: add link)
_____________________________________

If it isn't Scheduler, use DGrep query with NormalizerJob activities as entry point of investigation.

 




.

customLinks.clientQuery:
let resourceType = Regex.Match(properties, "SlimResourceType=\[([^\]]+)\]").Groups[1].Value
let failureReason = Regex.Match(properties, "FailureReason=\[([^\]]+)\]").Groups[1].Value
groupby resourceType, failureReason let count = count()
orderby count desc

Monitor is looking the length of the queue for segmented full sync job.
______________
Investigation steps:

1. Look on Normalizer queue. If there is significant change of level, it can be an issue.
If it is a case look to NormalizerFullyncQueueLength for actions:  https://jarvis-west.dc.ad.msft.net/?page=settings&mode=mdm&account=AzureResourcesTopology&namespace=ResourcesCacheProvider&metric=FinalSnapshotStatus&tab=monitors&monitor=IngestionFailure#/

2. Look on domain issues level increase(decrease).
If some big resource provider starts (stops) having some issues, it will create an incident.
Look to attached domain issues dashboard for details.
In case if provider starts to have some issues, create incidents for the provider.
Note: be carefully with error codes connected to api-version/provider. It can be caused by bug in our side, especially in Api Version cache.
If this is a domain issue and it has been active for a while you have the option of 
i) filtering out the types from ingestion (Onenote: Update ResourceFilterconfigs) 
ii) or two contacting the partner team to make them aware of the domain issue
